            <script src="//platform.linkedin.com/in.js" type="text/javascript">
  lang: en_US
</script>
<script type="IN/Share" data-url="http://www.wired.com/2013/07/a-little-rebellion-is-a-good-thing-the-rise-of-shadow-it/" data-counter="right"></script>        </li>
            <li class="pinterest-small">
            <a href="//www.pinterest.com/pin/create/button/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.wired.com%2F2013%2F07%2Fa-little-rebellion-is-a-good-thing-the-rise-of-shadow-it%2F&media=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.wired.com%2Fwp-content%2Fuploads%2Fimages_blogs%2Finsights%2F2013%2F03%2Fitadmin_660.jpg&description=A Little Rebellion is a Good Thing: The Rise of Shadow IT" data-pin-do="buttonPin" data-pin-config="beside" target="_blank">
	<img src="//assets.pinterest.com/images/pidgets/pin_it_button.png" />
</a>
        </li>
    </ul>
		<div class="entry">
			<span itemprop="articleBody"><p><div id="attachment_11600" style="width: 670px" class="wp-caption aligncenter"><img src="http://www.wired.com/insights/wp-content/uploads/2013/03/itadmin_660.jpg" alt="" title="itadmin_660" width="660" height="330" class="size-full wp-image-11600"><p class="wp-caption-text">Is shadow IT building in your org? <em>Image: bnilsen/Flickr</em></p></div>
</p><p>Ten years ago, I was a young sales executive at IBM selling DB2. We were in a big RFP against Oracle for a very large enterprise deal. Both sides were throwing everything they had at it, jockeying for position, wining and dining senior management and deploying large technical sales teams, but when the RFP closed and the decision was made, IBM and Oracle both lost to MySQL. Who wasn&rsquo;t even in the RFP, wasn&rsquo;t part of the corporate standard, and never even sent in a salesperson.</p>
<p>MySQL beat out two heavily funded sales efforts for one simple reason: during the eight-month RFP process, the developers deployed MySQL and had it working successfully, totally unbeknownst to senior IT or purchasing managers. Regardless of any corporate standard, no one was going to tinker with a working system or trump the developers. In fact, MySQL was quickly added to the standard at that point.</p>
<p>This trend of developer-focused open source projects and services supplanting traditional vendors has exploded in the last ten years. More and more tools are accessible via open source, as freemium services or free download. As a result, developers can find, test and deploy the tools they want. They can run their own proof of concept (POC) without getting dragged into a cumbersome sales engagement, or worse, paying for Oracle or IBM to perform the POC on their behalf.</p>
<p>In traditional software, expensive sales teams spend months selling to a senior IT manager who had a multi-million dollar budget and care about how well the products worked within IT&mdash;how easily it is managed, how well it integrates to SAP, and how secure it is. Ease of use has never been high on the list.</p>
<p>That&rsquo;s over.</p>
<p>Now, developers make independent buying and technology decisions. Shadow IT, led by developers, is deciding its own stacks, tool sets, and deployment environment. They&rsquo;re making critical technology decisions based on what&rsquo;s best for their user experience, for monetization flexibility and speed to market. Corporate IT strategy and standards are not high on this list.</p>
<p>Good or bad, the &ldquo;enterprise&rdquo;&rdquo; is no longer the customer for many B2B technology companies. For infrastructure technology like compute and storage to SMS messaging to application monitoring, the developer has become the primary customer.</p>
<p>The change is profound for vendors who now have to sell their products developer-by-developer, project-by-project. And that&rsquo;s radically different from selling to a CIO or Director of IT.</p>
<p>Stephen O&rsquo;Grady has done a great job covering what this means for vendors in &ldquo;<a href="http://thenewkingmakers.com/" target="_blank">The New Kingmakers</a>.&rdquo; You don&rsquo;t have to look far to see the rapid expansion of software service businesses with a developer-focused sale: Twilio, Sendgrid, Stripe, not to mention the biggest of the bunch, AWS.</p>
<p>But what about for buyers?</p>
<p>For developers, the rise of Shadow IT creates additional responsibility. If you&rsquo;re the developer who implemented a service incorrectly, the heat is on you if it is compromised, and you&rsquo;re working with less of a safety net.</p>
<p>For CIOs, the revolution has come. Because developer needs for usability and speed are legitimate, rather than battle to maintain security and manageability, a better approach is to ensure they have the tools to protect themselves as they work.</p>
<p><em>Alex Salazar is co-founder and CEO of Stormpath.</em></p>
